  <h3 class="subsection-heading">11.1.3 Useful Operations & Functions</h3>

  <div class="table-container">
  <table class="doc-table doc-table--categories">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Category</th>
        <th>Operation / Function</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="5">Matrix / Vector</th>
    <td>A + B<br>A - B<br>A * B</td>
    <td>Matrix/vector addition, subtraction, and multiplication</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A * s<br>A / s</td>
    <td>Scalar multiplication and division</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.transpose()</td>
    <td>Matrix/vector transpose</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.inverse()</td>
    <td>Matrix inverse (use only for small fixed-size matrices; prefer decompositions for large ones)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.determinant()</td>
    <td>Matrix determinant</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="4">Vector</th>
    <td>A.norm()<br>A.squaredNorm()</td>
    <td>Euclidean (L2) norm and its square — prefer squaredNorm() to avoid a sqrt</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.normalized()<br>A.normalize()</td>
    <td>Returns a unit-length copy (normalized) or normalizes in-place (normalize)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>a.dot(b)</td>
    <td>Dot product of two vectors</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>a.cross(b)</td>
    <td>Cross product of two 3D vectors</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="3">Coefficient-Wise</th>
    <td>A.cwiseProduct(B)<br>A.cwiseQuotient(B)<br>A.cwiseAbs()</td>
    <td>Coefficient-wise product, quotient, and absolute value</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.sum()<br>A.prod()<br>A.mean()<br>A.minCoeff()<br>A.maxCoeff()</td>
    <td>Reductions: sum, product, mean, min, and max over all coefficients</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Eigen::Array&lt;Scalar, Rows, Cols&gt;</td>
    <td>Element-wise array type for coefficient-wise operations instead of linear algebra</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="4">Submatrix / Slicing</th>
    <td>A.block(i, j, rows, cols)<br>A.topLeftCorner(rows, cols)<br>A.bottomRightCorner(rows, cols)</td>
    <td>Extract a submatrix block by position or corner</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.row(i)<br>A.col(j)</td>
    <td>Access a single row or column as a vector expression</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.head(n)<br>A.tail(n)<br>A.segment(i, n)</td>
    <td>Extract the first n, last n, or n elements starting at i from a vector</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.resize(rows, cols)<br>A.conservativeResize(rows, cols)</td>
    <td>Resize a dynamic matrix; conservativeResize preserves existing coefficients</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="2">Initialization</th>
    <td>A.setZero()<br>A.setOnes()<br>A.setIdentity()<br>A.setRandom()</td>
    <td>Fill a matrix with zeros, ones, identity, or random values in-place</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Eigen::MatrixXd::Zero(r, c)<br>Eigen::MatrixXd::Identity(r, c)<br>Eigen::MatrixXd::Ones(r, c)</td>
    <td>Static constructors for common initializations</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="3">Decompositions &amp; Solvers</th>
    <td>A.lu()<br>A.llt()<br>A.ldlt()<br>A.colPivHouseholderQr()</td>
    <td>Matrix decompositions: LU, Cholesky (LLT / LDLT), and QR — preferred over inverse() for solving systems</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>A.lu().solve(b)<br>A.llt().solve(b)</td>
    <td>Solve the linear system Ax = b using a decomposition</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>Eigen::JacobiSVD&lt;&gt;<br>Eigen::BDCSVD&lt;&gt;<br>Eigen::SelfAdjointEigenSolver&lt;&gt;</td>
    <td>SVD (JacobiSVD for small, BDCSVD for large matrices) and eigenvalue decomposition for symmetric matrices</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="3">Quaternion</th>
    <td>q.toRotationMatrix()</td>
    <td>Convert a quaternion to a 3×3 rotation matrix</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>q.slerp(t, q2)</td>
    <td>Spherical linear interpolation between two quaternions</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>q.conjugate()<br>q.inverse()</td>
    <td>Quaternion conjugate and inverse (conjugate is sufficient for unit quaternions)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="2">Transforms</th>
    <td>T.translation()<br>T.rotation()<br>T.linear()</td>
    <td>Extract translation, rotation, and linear part from an Affine3 or Isometry3 transform</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td>T1 * T2<br>T.inverse()</td>
    <td>Compose transforms and compute the inverse transform</td>
  </tr>
</tbody>
  </table>
</div>

  <h3 class="subsection-heading">11.1.4 Eigen::Map</h3>

  <p>
  <strong><code class="path-inline">Eigen::Map</code></strong> creates an Eigen object that references an existing block of memory <strong>without copying its contents</strong>. This makes it possible to work directly with data stored in other Eigen objects, C arrays, or <strong><code class="path-inline">std::vector</code></strong>
  </p>

